# bug(aria/combobox): `KeyboardEventManager` throws on synthetic `keydown` with no `key` (browser autofill)

## Is this a regression?

No — present since the `@angular/aria` combobox/listbox primitives were introduced.

## Description

`KeyboardEventManager._isMatch` reads `event.key.toLowerCase()` without guarding against `event.key` being `undefined`:

```js
// @angular/aria v22.0.0 — fesm2022/_violations-chunk.mjs
_isMatch(event, key, modifiers, options) {
  ...
  const keyStr = typeof key === 'string' ? key : key();
  return keyStr.toLowerCase() === event.key.toLowerCase(); // 💥 event.key is undefined
}
```

Browsers (notably Chrome) dispatch a **synthetic `keydown` with `event.key === undefined`** as part of form **autofill**. When that event reaches the `ngCombobox` keydown handler (`ComboboxPattern.onKeydown` → `KeyboardEventManager.handle` → `matcher` → `_isMatch`), it throws:

```
ERROR TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'toLowerCase')
    at KeyboardEventManager._isMatch (_violations-chunk.mjs:86:47)
    at Object.matcher (_violations-chunk.mjs:56:30)
    at KeyboardEventManager.handle (_violations-chunk.mjs:17:18)
    at ComboboxPattern.onKeydown (private.mjs:102:22)
    at Combobox_keydown_HostBindingHandler (combobox.mjs:91:31)
```

The same `_isMatch` is used by every widget that relies on `KeyboardEventManager` (listbox, menu, tabs, etc.), so any of them focused during/around an autofill can hit this. Setting `autocomplete="off"` on the input does **not** prevent the browser from dispatching the malformed `keydown`.

## Reproduction

Minimal `ngCombobox` inside a `<form>`:

```html
<form>
  <!-- A field the browser will offer to autofill -->
  <input name="name" autocomplete="name" />

  <input
    ngCombobox
    #combobox="ngCombobox"
    autocomplete="off"
    [(value)]="query" />
  <ng-template ngComboboxPopup [combobox]="combobox">
    <div ngComboboxWidget ngListbox>
      @for (opt of options; track opt) {
        <div ngOption [value]="opt" [label]="opt">{{ opt }}</div>
      }
    </div>
  </ng-template>
</form>
```

Steps:

1. Have a saved autofill profile in Chrome.
2. Focus the form and accept a browser autofill suggestion for the name field.
3. The synthetic `keydown` (with `key === undefined`) reaches the combobox handler → `TypeError` thrown in the console.

It can also be reproduced synthetically:

```js
document.querySelector('[ngCombobox]')
  .dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keydown', { bubbles: true })); // key defaults to ''
// and, closer to autofill, an event whose `key` getter yields undefined:
const e = new Event('keydown', { bubbles: true });
Object.defineProperty(e, 'key', { value: undefined });
document.querySelector('[ngCombobox]').dispatchEvent(e);
```

## Expected behavior

A `keydown` that carries no usable `key` should be ignored by `KeyboardEventManager` rather than throwing an uncaught `TypeError` into the application.

## Environment

- `@angular/aria`: 22.0.0
- Angular: 22.x
- Browser: Chrome (autofill)

## Possible solution

Guard the key comparison in `_isMatch` so a missing `event.key` simply fails to match instead of throwing:

```js
_isMatch(event, key, modifiers, options) {
  if (!hasModifiers(event, modifiers)) {
    return false;
  }
  if (event.repeat && options?.ignoreRepeat !== false) {
    return false;
  }
  // Synthetic events (e.g. browser autofill) can omit `key`.
  if (event.key == null) {
    return false;
  }
  if (key instanceof RegExp) {
    return key.test(event.key);
  }
  const keyStr = typeof key === 'string' ? key : key();
  return keyStr.toLowerCase() === event.key.toLowerCase();
}
```

(The `RegExp` branch also benefits, since `key.test(undefined)` coerces to the string `"undefined"` and can match unexpectedly.)

## Workaround (for anyone hitting this before a fix lands)

Register a **capture-phase** `keydown` listener on an ancestor of the `ngCombobox` input and drop events with no `key` before they reach the library handler. Capture-phase ancestor listeners run before the input's target-phase handler, so this reliably intercepts the bad event (a bubble-phase listener on the input itself competes with the library's host listener in registration order and is not reliable):

```ts
@Directive({ selector: '[autofillKeydownGuard]' })
export class AutofillKeydownGuard {
  constructor() {
    const host = inject(ElementRef).nativeElement as HTMLElement;
    host.addEventListener(
      'keydown',
      (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
        if (e.key == null) e.stopImmediatePropagation();
      },
      { capture: true },
    );
  }
}
```

Apply it to a wrapper element around the combobox (e.g. via `hostDirectives` on your wrapping component).


